          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Behind the Deck series. Vellup Tactics.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8900'>Chris "Fire83" Neathery</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8900&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 28, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I would like to welcome all readers to a series of delving into decks and advanced building and reasoning behind deck types.<br>
<br>
 For the inaugural article, I will examine a favorite deck type of mine: Vellup Tactics. The deck goes by many names, Vellup assault, Stupid Arderial Tricks, Delia Bash etc. There is a current and running theme in the deck design. First I would like to dish out the stripped basics of the deck itself.<br>
<br>
Magi<br>
Delia <br>
Ora <br>
Sorreah<br>
<br>
Creatures<br>
Xyx x3<br>
Xyx minor x3<br>
Xyx Elder x2<br>
Vellup x3<br>
Elder Vellup x2<br>
<br>
Spells<br>
Shock wave x3<br>
Cataclysm x3<br>
<br>
Relics<br>
Rayje&#39;s Belt x2<br>
Warrior&#39;s Boots x3<br>
<br>
Now there will be a of number variations based on the metagame of the area and on what a player may have, but this is the dream base for the deck.<br>
<br>
The first look will be into the magi and their order. Predominately first is Delia. <br>
  She is a 12-6 Arderial magi(12 starting energy and 6 energize) and has two abilities. One is the effect strengthen which allows any Vellup creature she plays to gain one energy. Her power, Recurring Dreams, allows her to pay one energy to fetch a Vellup creature from the discard pile and put it into her hand. Her starting cards are Vellup and Shooting Star.<br>
  Beyond her simple card break down is the power of her energize and recurring dreams power. She may effectively grab an Elder Vellup each turn that may have been discarded in some way last turn and play it. The same applies for the normal Vellup as well. This is fine and dandy till you realize that every time you play an Elder Vellup you are getting another creature from you deck and putting it into your hand. This thins your deck leaving cards that may be referred to as &quot;utility. <br>
  Utility is a card besides one of the basic deck structure used to defeat you opponent. Examples would be shooting star, thunderquake or bottomless pit. Each is not necessary for the deck to function but does allow for timed use to turn games. This is often essential in mirror matches and tough duels. Often it is who has the best utility at the right time when deciding a winner oame.<br>
  In short, the main purpose of Delia is to repeatedly play Vellups to pound the opponent and thin out your deck while doing so. This way, when Delia is defeated, if she is defeated, your next magi is ready with many cards in hand, hopefully.<br>
      Most often as a following magi, Ora comes on to the scene fully prepared to dish out punishment. She is a veterain from the Base set of Magi-Nation. Her stats for a refresher are:<br>
Arderial Magi<br>
Ora <br>
12<br>
energize-5<br>
starting Xyx minor, Xyx elder, shooting star<br>
effect- strengthen- when ever you play an Arderial creature, you may add one energy to that creature.<br>
  Ora is a great middle magi who often finishes games in several turns. She does best when one plays down three Xyx minors and begins pumping them up. Once this starts, she is difficult to stop. Sometimes when a finish is absolutely necessary, she may use cataclysm and Xyx to finish a final magi.<br>
Last and certainly not least is Sorreah. He has some what of an oppressing personality. He simply suppresses powers, and for free too. His stats are<br>
Arderial Magi <br>
Sorreah<br>
13<br>
energize 5<br>
Starting any two Arderial spells<br>
effect suppress Effects and powers on other magi may not be used.<br>
Though the magi is a bit of a party pooper and a downer he cleans up effectively by using the same finish as Ora, grab a cataclysm from the discard or deck (if you have no other Arderial spells in the discard pile) then use Xyx to wipe energy from a defenseless magi.<br>
  Magi order may follow several paths. The most common are Delia, Ora, Sorreah or Sorreah, Delia, Ora. For most intensive purposes, the orders reflect Vellup tactics and Anti-Delia Vellup tactics respectively. Sometimes to beat a deck you must warp the principles to your own agenda.<br>
<br>
Creatures are self explanatory. The Xyx creatures bring the power and the Vellups bring the power with mass card drawing and horde maneuvers. <br>
<br>
The spells are basic with shockwave and Cataclysm. These are the only two Arderial spells in the deck so that Sorreah is not forced to grab two shooting stars from the discard pile when he could get a Cataclysm or Shockwave instead.<br>
<br>
As with the other two subsets, the relics are simple. The belt prevents powers like burrow or other problems from being problems. The Warrior&#39;s boots are what would be called mandatory utility. The deck is aggressive in nature, and so needs the fast footwear.<br>
<br>
As many have noticed by now, there are only 24 cards in the basic deck design. What is listed is all that is &quot;mandatory&quot; for the deck. This leaves 16 card slots for meta-game thinking for your environment. Again it&#39;s another reason for the versatility of the deck. In essence, it can make a square peg fit into a round hole by making minor adjustments.<br>
<br>
I hope this article has been enlightening. May all your ventures into the Moonlands be productive.<br>
<br>
Chris Fire83 Neathery<br>
Firerose83 to those who care.<br>
